text.text: Antiquities from Buddhist period, Maurya period, Mughal period to Pal period are present here.  According to information, the word Anguttarap has been used for Begusarai in the ancient Buddhist texts Anguttara and Mahavagga. Begusarai district's Jaimangalagarh, Naulagarh, Virpur, Baripura, Vikrampur, Nurullahpur, Singhaul, Rajwada, Garhpura, Ejni, Ekamba, Malipur, Morattar, Meghaul  Abundant amount of historical material has been found from places like Vasudevpur, Kaith, Baraith etc.  These historical heritage are preserved in the Begusarai Museum. Establishment of Begusarai Museum Begusarai Museum was established in the year 1981.  What are the preserved pottery sculptures in the museum: The museum has displays of pottery from the Mauryan period to the Pal period.

text.text: Established in the year 1981, this government museum houses physical evidences that witnessed the rich cultural history of Begusarai. Stone sculptures of Lord Buddha, Lord Ganesh, Sun God and Lord Vishnu etc. can be seen here. Coins, ranging from the period of Pal rule, Mauryan Rule to the end of British Era in India are treasured in the museum. Other attractions include manuscripts, terracotta and pottery specimens. Art objects are collected from all around the town, though the centuries.
